# Notes Command Line Genomics Carpentry



# history <- gives list of recent commands (use !commandnumber to repeat a command)

# Shortcuts
  # Ctrl+C will cancel the command you are writing, and give you a fresh prompt.
  # Ctrl+R will do a reverse-search through your command history. This is very useful.
  # Ctrl+L or the clear command will clear your screen.

# less (like a read only cat)
  # Space 	to go forward
  # b 	to go backward
  # g 	to go to the beginning
  # G 	to go to the end
  # q 	to quit
  # /   to search forward (make sure you're at the beginning)
  # ?   to search backward (capitalization matters for these)

# head and tail
  # use -n option to say number of lines

# .fastq format notes
  # 1 	Always begins with ‘@’ and then information about the read
  # 2 	The actual DNA sequence
  # 3 	Always begins with a ‘+’ and sometimes the same info in line 1
  # 4 	Has a string of characters which represent the quality scores; must have same number of characters as line 2

# Permissions
  # ls -l flag will show permissions on files
    # rwx or dashes on user, then group, then other
  # chmod -w subtracts writing permissions (useful to not accidentally overwrite)

# grep
  # it's like ctr - f for looking inside of files
  # -A and -B arguments for showing a particular number of lines before/after

